messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

- Full path:
  /consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas/{printingSchemaID}

- All HTTP methods acceptable: false

- HEAD: false
- POST: false
- OPTIONS: false
- TRACE: false
- GET: false
- PUT: true
- DELETE: true
- PATCH: false

Explanation:
- The controller class has no class-level @RequestMapping, so the full path is exactly the value in the method-level annotations.
- The editConsumerPrintingSchema method is annotated with
  @RequestMapping(value = "/consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas/{printingSchemaID}", method = RequestMethod.PUT)
  which makes PUT for /consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas/{printingSchemaID} acceptable.
- There is also a deleteConsumerPrintingSchema method annotated with
  @RequestMapping(value = "/consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas/{printingSchemaID}", method = RequestMethod.DELETE)
  so DELETE for the same path is acceptable.
- No other methods are annotated for this exact path. The class does define GET and POST handlers, but those are for /consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas (no {printingSchemaID}) — they do not apply to the path with {printingSchemaID}.
- Per your instruction, I based acceptability strictly on explicit code annotations. I did not assume framework-provided implicit handling (e.g., automatic HEAD/OPTIONS responses) — therefore HEAD, OPTIONS, TRACE, PATCH, GET and POST are reported as false for this exact path.
